    <text>
        <body>
            <head>9. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                    (<persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI">Clark</persName>) to Secretary of State
                    <persName corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName>, Secretary of Defense
                    <persName corresp="recg0WDsRQgtuIKMw">Weinberger</persName>, Director of Central
                of Intelligence <persName corresp="rec7YPjp5UCcrZuXE">Casey</persName>, the Chairman
                of the Joint Chiefs of Staff (<persName corresp="recZHbNIqHWs3PQzI"
                >Jones</persName>), and the Director of the <orgName corresp="reckjQkUajOv3dbTz"
                    >Arms Control and Disarmament Agency</orgName> (<persName
                    corresp="recM8U5HOaBRfTDmg">Rostow</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d9fn1">Source: <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma"
                        >National Security Council</orgName>, National Security Council
                    Institutional Files, Box SR—101, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"><orgName
                            corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName></gloss> 00046 <gloss
                        target="#t_RWR_1">RWR</gloss> 4/21/82 <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                            corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss>. Top
                    Secret.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1982-04-23"
                        >April 23, 1982</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Preparations for <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O"
                            type="event">START</rs></gloss>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>In the wake of the <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security
                    Council</orgName> meeting of April 21, the <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                    >President</persName> has directed the following analyses as a basis for
                reaching decisions on the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United
                    States</placeName> negotiating position for the <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                        corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss>
                negotiations.</p>
            <p>The work of the <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O"
                        type="event">START</rs></gloss> Interdepartmental Group has been extremely
                worthwhile and well done. This work should now be elevated to the Senior
                Interdepartmental Group co-chaired by the Departments of <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> and <orgName
                    corresp="recjQ97iMHKp6vwlA">Defense</orgName>, which should undertake analyses
                forthwith and produce a paper containing the following elements:</p>
            <p>—Options for the Units of Account.</p>
            <p>—Interim restraints to which we might subscribe without risk to our <rs
                    corresp="recooe4dhYZz894vH" type="topic">security interests</rs>.</p>
            <p>—Other issues, e.g. refires, mobiles, <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs
                        corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs></gloss>
                <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs>, etc.</p>
            <p>As an important basis for the <gloss target="#t_SIG_1">SIG</gloss>’s analyses, the
                    <orgName corresp="recjQ97iMHKp6vwlA">Department of Defense</orgName> should
                forward to the <gloss target="#t_SIG_1">SIG</gloss> the results of an analysis of
                absolute weapons requirements essential to the support of the national strategy
                under alternative <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O"
                        type="event">START</rs></gloss> outcomes.</p>
            <p>The required paper should be forwarded by the <gloss target="#t_SIG_1">SIG</gloss> to
                the <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security Council</orgName> not
                later than <gloss target="#t_COB_1">COB</gloss> May 1, 1982. This paper will form
                the basis for an <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"><orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma"
                        >NSC</orgName></gloss> discussion and for subsequent decisions on <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event"
                    >START</rs></gloss> during the week of May 3.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">William P. Clark</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d9fn2">
                        <persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI">Clark</persName> signed the memorandum
                            “<persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI">William Clark</persName>” above
                        his typed signature.</note>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
